Global Gastronomy.title: Steaks
Global Gastronomy.description: High-quality cuts of meat cooked to preference

Global Gastronomy.title: Barbecue Fish
Global Gastronomy.description: Fish grilled or smoked over an open fire or on a barbecue

Global Gastronomy.title: Ceviche
Global Gastronomy.description: A seafood dish made from fresh raw fish cured in citrus juices

Global Gastronomy.title: Curry
Global Gastronomy.description: A variety of dishes originating in the Indian subcontinent that use a complex combination of spices

Global Gastronomy.title: Carpaccio
Global Gastronomy.description: Dish of thinly sliced raw meat or fish, drizzled with olive oil

Global Gastronomy.title: Hummus
Global Gastronomy.description: A thick, creamy paste made from ground chickpeas and other ingredients

Global Gastronomy.title: Falafel
Global Gastronomy.description: A deep-fried ball or patty made from ground chickpeas, fava beans, or both

Global Gastronomy.title: Crème Brûlée
Global Gastronomy.description: A rich custard base topped with a layer of hardened caramelized sugar

Global Gastronomy.title: Éclair
Global Gastronomy.description: A pastry made with choux dough filled with a cream and topped with a flavored icing

Global Gastronomy.title: Tahini
Global Gastronomy.description: A condiment made from toasted ground hulled sesame

Global Gastronomy.title: Greek Salad
Global Gastronomy.description: A salad made primarily of tomatoes, cucumbers, olives, feta cheese, and a dressing

Global Gastronomy.title: Nicoise Salad
Global Gastronomy.description: A salad originating from Nice, France, typically made of tomatoes, hard-boiled eggs, Niçoise olives, anchovies, and various green beans

Global Gastronomy.title: Brie cheese
Global Gastronomy.description: Brie is a soft cow's-milk cheese named after Brie, the French region from which it originated.

Global Gastronomy.title: Camembert
Global Gastronomy.description: Camembert is a moist, soft, creamy, surface-ripened cow's milk cheese. It was first made in the late 18th century in Camembert, Normandy, in northwest France.

Global Gastronomy.title: Buche cheese
Global Gastronomy.description: Buche de Chevre is an exquisite soft cheese made from goat's milk and produced in the Poitou-Charentes region in the Loire Valley of central France.

Global Gastronomy.title: Burrata
Global Gastronomy.description: Burrata is an Italian cow milk cheese made from mozzarella and cream

Global Gastronomy.title: Amba
Global Gastronomy.description: Amba or anba is a tangy mango pickle condiment of Indo-Iraqi origin.

Global Gastronomy.title: Donar kebab
Global Gastronomy.description: Doner kebab, also spelled as döner kebab, is a dish of Turkish origin made of meat cooked on a vertical rotisserie.

Russian Food.title: Pelmeni
Russian Food.description: Pelmeni are dumplings of Russian cuisine that consist of a filling wrapped in thin, unleavened dough. It is debated whether they originated in Ural or Siberia. Pelmeni have been described as the heart of Russian cuisine

Russian Food.title: Blini
Russian Food.description: Traditionally also called a blin is a Russian and more broadly Eastern European pancake traditionally made from buckwheat flour or nowadays wheat and served with smetana, tvorog, butter, caviar and other garnishes.

Russian Food.title: Berries
Russian Food.description: Berries are very tasty and useful gifts from nature. They are a delight for even the most fastidious taste, loved by young and old. Berries are fragrant and fresh, useful for your memory and heart.

Russian Food.title: Caviar
Russian Food.description: Caviar is a food consisting of salt-cured roe of the family Acipenseridae. Caviar is considered a delicacy and is eaten as a garnish or spread.

Russian Food.title: Vodka
Russian Food.description: Vodka is a clear distilled alcoholic beverage. Different varieties originated in Poland, Russia, and Sweden. Vodka is composed mainly of water and ethanol but sometimes with traces of impurities and flavourings.

Russian Food.title: Birch Sap
Russian Food.description: Birch sap, birch water or birch juice is the sap directly tapped from birch trees, Betula pubescens, Betula pendula, Betula lenta, Betula papyrifera, and Betula fontinalis.

Russian Food.title: Pirozhki
Russian Food.description: Pirozhki are foremost, Russian baked or fried yeast-leavened boat-shaped buns with a variety of fillings. Pirozhki are a popular street food and comfort food in Eastern Europe.

Russian Food.title: Plombir
Russian Food.description: Plombir is a type of Soviet ice cream made with vanilla, cream, eggs, and sugar. It was subject to national Soviet standards, which required that it be made with natural ingredients and meet specifications for consistency and fat and sugar content.

Russian Food.title: Draniki
Russian Food.description: Draniki are shallow-fried pancakes of grated or ground potato, matzo meal or flour and a binding ingredient such as egg or applesauce, often flavored with grated garlic or onion and seasonings.

Russian Food.title: Lisichky
Russian Food.description: Cantharellus cibarius is a species of golden chanterelle mushroom in the genus Cantharellus. It is also known as girolle. It grows in Europe from Scandinavia to the Mediterranean Basin, mainly in deciduous and coniferous forests.

Russian Food.title: Ukha
Russian Food.description: Ukha is a clear Russian soup, made from various types of fish such as bream, wels catfish, northern pike, or even ruffe.

Russian Food.title: Dark Bread
Russian Food.description: Dark rye bread is a traditional Russian bread made with dark rye flour, molasses, fresh coriander seeds and caraway. It's classically made using rye sourdough starter, but can be made with regular starter or yeast.

Russian Food.title: Borscht
Russian Food.description: Borscht is a sour soup, made with meat stock, vegetables and seasonings.

Russian Food.title: Smetannik
Russian Food.description: Tort Smetannik means a cake with sour cream.

Russian Food.title: Shuba
Russian Food.description: Shuba salad, or “Herring Under a Fur Coat,” is a layered salad of pickled herring fillets, finely chopped onion, beets, carrots

Russian Food.title: Olivier
Russian Food.description: Olivier salad is a traditional salad dish in Russian cuisine, which is also popular in other post-Soviet countries and around the world.

Russian Food.title: Medovik
Russian Food.description: Medovik is a layer cake popular in countries of the former Soviet Union. The identifying ingredients are honey and smetana (sour cream) or condensed milk.

Russian Food.title: Napolion
Russian Food.description: Napoleon cake is a perfectly moist and deliciously creamy dessert made of crunchy puff pastry and silky pastry cream

Russian Food.title: Sharlotka
Russian Food.description: Sharlotka is a classic Russian apple cake. In some parts of the world, it’s known as the French Apple cake.

Russian Food.title: Kyiv cake
Russian Food.description: Kyiv cake is a dessert cake produced in Kyiv, Ukraine since December 6, 1956 by the Karl Marx Confectionery Factory which is now a subsidiary of the Roshen corporation.

Russian Food.title: Bird milk
Russian Food.description: Bird's milk is a Central European confectionery originating in Poland. It is a small, chocolate-covered bar with a soft marshmallow-like interior.

Russian Food.title: Plov
Russian Food.description: Pilaf or pilau is a rice dish, or in some regions, a wheat dish, whose recipe usually involves cooking in stock or broth.

Russian Food.title: Dried Fish
Russian Food.description: Fresh fish rapidly deteriorates unless some way can be found to preserve it.

Russian Food.title: Salted and marinated Fish
Russian Food.description: Salted fish, such as kippered herring or dried and salted cod, is fish cured with dry salt and thus preserved for later eating

Jewish Food.title: Gefilte fish
Jewish Food.description: A dish made from a poached mixture of ground deboned fish, such as carp, whitefish, or pike

Jewish Food.title: Chopped liver
Jewish Food.description: A spread popular in Jewish cuisine made by chopping or grinding liver

Jewish Food.title: P'tcha
Jewish Food.description: A traditional Jewish dish made from jellied calves' feet

Jewish Food.title: Chraime
Jewish Food.description: A spicy fish stew dish in Jewish cuisine

Jewish Food.title: Chrain
Jewish Food.description: A type of horseradish paste used in Jewish cuisine

Jewish Food.title: Chicken soup
Jewish Food.description: A soup made from chicken, simmered in water, usually with various other ingredients

Jewish Food.title: Knedalach
Jewish Food.description: Dumplings often served in chicken soup

Jewish Food.title: Matzah brei
Jewish Food.description: A dish of Ashkenazi Jewish origin made from matzah fried with eggs

Jewish Food.title: Lox
Jewish Food.description: Lox is a fillet of brined salmon, which may be smoked.

Jewish Food.title: Latke
Jewish Food.description: A type of potato pancake or fritter in Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine that is traditionally prepared to celebrate Hanukkah

Jewish Food.title: Forshmak
Jewish Food.description: It's probably the most authentically Jewish herring recipe. The word itself is Yiddish for “pre-taste”–that is, an appetizer, meant to set your taste buds going

Georgian Food.title: Khinkali
Georgian Food.description: A Georgian dumpling filled with spiced meat

Georgian Food.title: Satsivi
Georgian Food.description: A thick paste made from walnuts and served cold

Georgian Food.title: Chakhokhbili
Georgian Food.description: A traditional Georgian dish made from stewed chicken

Georgian Food.title: Badrijani Nigvzit
Georgian Food.description: Eggplant rolls filled with a walnut paste

Georgian Food.title: Lobio
Georgian Food.description: A Georgian dish made with kidney beans

Georgian Food.title: Kharcho
Georgian Food.description: A spicy soup made with beef, rice, and walnuts

Georgian Food.title: Ajapsandali
Georgian Food.description: A vegetarian dish made from eggplants, potatoes, and tomatoes
